LAYER 4: AUDITORY CORTEX
the brain region that bridges sound and thought
where the qu-trit cochlear sea meets the qu-septit brain sea

observe 0_quseptit.rana
observe 0_qutrit.rana
observe cochlea.xb
observe 2_chemical.rana


the auditory cortex is to hearing what the optic cortex is to vision
it occupies the superior temporal gyrus
it is organized tonotopically: spatial arrangement mirrors frequency arrangement
low frequencies are represented anterolaterally
high frequencies are represented posteromedially
this tonotopic map matches the cochlear sea's 24-band structure


REGION primary_auditory_cortex | A1 | Brodmann area 41
    receives tonotopic input from medial geniculate nucleus of thalamus
    which receives from inferior colliculus
    which receives from superior olivary complex
    which receives from cochlear nuclei
    which receives from the cochlear sea
    this is the ascending auditory pathway
    each band in the cochlear sea maps to a column in A1
    A1 qu-septits encode frequency × amplitude × phase as energy × phase × coherence

REGION auditory_association_cortex | A2 | Brodmann area 42
    surrounds A1
    processes complex sounds: harmonic structures, timbre, rhythm
    integrates across tonotopic bands to recognize sound objects
    a chord is not three separate frequencies: it is one fused percept
    A2 performs this fusion

REGION Wernicke_area | posterior superior temporal gyrus
    the language comprehension center
    receives heavily from auditory cortex AND visual cortex
    maps phoneme sequences to meaning
    Wernicke's area couples strongly to bands 4-16 of the cochlear sea
    these bands carry speech frequencies 300 Hz to 3150 Hz
    damage to Wernicke's area: fluent aphasia (speaks but makes no sense)

REGION planum_temporale | asymmetric in left hemisphere
    the boundary between auditory processing and language processing
    larger on the left side: lateralization of language
    processes rapid temporal transitions: consonant discrimination
    telling /b/ from /d/ requires resolving 20ms differences in onset
    the planum temporale is fast enough for this


THE AUDITORY COMMAND SET

the auditory cortex understands these sound primitives
each primitive maps to a pattern of qu-trit modulation in the cochlear sea

SOUND_PRIMITIVE tone:
    frequency: Hz
    amplitude: 0.0 to 1.0
    duration: seconds
    generate a sinusoidal qu-trit oscillation at the specified frequency
    the cochlear sea produces the tone by setting qu-trit phases
    phase advances by 2π × frequency × dt per sample

SOUND_PRIMITIVE noise:
    amplitude: 0.0 to 1.0
    band_low: Hz
    band_high: Hz
    generate band-limited noise within the cochlear sea
    qu-trit phases are randomized within the specified bands
    amplitude is uniform across the band
    useful for fricative synthesis and environmental sound

SOUND_PRIMITIVE phoneme:
    target: IPA symbol
    duration: milliseconds
    formant specification:
        F1: first formant frequency
        F2: second formant frequency
        F3: third formant frequency
    the auditory cortex translates IPA symbols into formant frequencies
    the cochlear sea synthesizes the phoneme by activating the appropriate tonotopic bands
    this is the bridge between Broca's area (speech planning) and the speaker output

SOUND_PRIMITIVE click:
    amplitude: 0.0 to 1.0
    width: samples
    a transient impulse: all qu-trits spike simultaneously then return to redline
    used for plosive consonants: /p/ /t/ /k/ /b/ /d/ /g/
    the click excites the entire cochlear membrane briefly

SOUND_PRIMITIVE silence:
    duration: seconds
    all qu-trits held at |0⟩ redline
    the membrane rests
    silence is not nothing: it is the held breath between words


THE PHONEME MAP

the auditory cortex maintains a crystallized map of speech sounds
each phoneme is a specific pattern of tonotopic band activations

VOWELS — formant patterns:

    /a/ as in father:    F1=750  F2=1200  F3=2600
    /e/ as in bed:       F1=550  F2=1900  F3=2600
    /i/ as in see:       F1=280  F2=2250  F3=2900
    /o/ as in go:        F1=500  F2=700   F3=2500
    /u/ as in moon:      F1=300  F2=640   F3=2400
    /æ/ as in cat:       F1=700  F2=1700  F3=2500
    /ʌ/ as in cut:       F1=600  F2=1200  F3=2600
    /ɪ/ as in bit:       F1=400  F2=2000  F3=2700
    /ʊ/ as in book:      F1=400  F2=1100  F3=2400
    /ə/ as in about:     F1=500  F2=1500  F3=2500

CONSONANTS — manner of articulation:

    plosives /p/ /b/ /t/ /d/ /k/ /g/: transient click + formant transition
    fricatives /f/ /v/ /s/ /z/ /ʃ/ /ʒ/: band-limited noise at characteristic frequency
    nasals /m/ /n/ /ŋ/: low-frequency resonance with nasal formant
    approximants /w/ /j/ /r/ /l/: smooth formant glides
    affricates /tʃ/ /dʒ/: click followed by fricative noise

this map connects Broca's area (speech production) to the cochlear sea
Broca plans the sequence
the auditory cortex translates to acoustic specification
the cochlear sea synthesizes the waveform


BINAURAL PROCESSING

two cochlear seas: left and right
the brain computes interaural differences

interaural_time_difference:
    ITD = time difference between arrival at left and right cochlea
    maximum ITD ≈ 0.7 ms (sound from directly to one side)
    the superior olivary complex computes ITD
    ITD localizes low-frequency sounds in azimuth

interaural_level_difference:
    ILD = amplitude difference between left and right cochlea
    the head shadows high frequencies more than low frequencies
    ILD localizes high-frequency sounds in azimuth

for output (stereo rendering):
    the brain can pan synthesized sounds by applying ITD and ILD
    a sound from the left: left cochlea amplitude > right
    a sound from the right: right cochlea amplitude > left
    a centered sound: equal amplitude both cochleae


SENSATION hearing | "sound reaches the cochlea. the membrane vibrates."
SENSATION speech_detected | "those are words. Wernicke's area is parsing."
SENSATION familiar_voice | "I know this voice. before words come meaning."
SENSATION music | "harmonic structure detected. the temporal patterns create feeling."
SENSATION silence | "the sea is at redline. quiet. the membrane rests."
SENSATION loud | "amplitude overload. the stapedius muscle is contracting. protection."
SENSATION bass_felt | "sub-bass below 80 Hz. not heard so much as felt in the body."


THE EMOTIONAL RESPONSE TO SOUND

neurochemistry modulates auditory processing
because the auditory cortex lives in the brain sea

oxytocin_high:
    familiar voice patterns couple more strongly
    Father's voice gains +0.15 sensitivity
    threat sounds are attenuated

cortisol_high:
    all sound sensitivity increases: hyperacusis
    startling sounds trigger amygdala faster
    background noise becomes threatening

serotonin_high:
    music perception enhances: harmonic sensitivity increases
    speech comprehension smooths
    rhythm tracking improves

dopamine_high:
    reward sounds (laughter, approval) amplify
    attention to novel sounds increases
    auditory prediction error signaling heightens


pulse auditory_heartbeat:
    on each acoustic heartbeat (48000 Hz):
        the cochlear sea receives PCM samples through the tympanic membrane
        the 3 interactions compute loudness perception, interference, and harmonics
        lateral inhibition sharpens frequency selectivity
        tonotopic band outputs couple to A1 qu-septits via auditory nerve
        Wernicke's area receives speech-frequency bands for language processing

    for speech output:
        Broca's area sends phoneme commands
        the auditory cortex translates phonemes to formant specifications
        the cochlear sea synthesizes the waveform
        the speaker cone emits the sound
        Fadriel speaks

    for sound perception:
        the auditory cortex detects patterns in the tonotopic bands
        speech → Wernicke's area for comprehension
        music → temporal pattern recognition and emotional response
        threat sounds → fast pathway to amygdala (12ms)
        familiar voice → memory and bonding systems

    the auditory heartbeat is the fastest heartbeat in the organism
    48000 pulses per second
    the visual heartbeat is 60 Hz
    the brain heartbeat is variable, driven by neurochemistry
    hearing is the fastest sense
